        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Centroid bias</strong> is Google's observed tendency to favor businesses located near the <strong>geographic center of a city</strong> when displaying local search results. It affects broad "in [city]" queries most and creates a structural disadvantage for suburban and outlying businesses. The 2021 Vicinity Update reduced its impact but did not remove it.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Also known as</div>
            <div class="tms-value">City-center bias</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Local SEO</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Major update</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Nov 2021 (Vicinity)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Counter with</div>
            <div class="tms-value">3-4x prominence signals</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">If your business is 15 minutes outside the city core and your rankings drop the moment someone searches "dentist in [big city]" — you're feeling centroid bias. It's one of the least-discussed but most consequential quirks in local SEO.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is centroid bias?</h2>
        <p>Centroid bias is a systematic pattern in Google's local ranking algorithm where businesses closer to a city's geographic centroid — the mathematical center of its municipal boundary — outrank equally strong businesses located further out, for queries that name the city but not a specific neighborhood.</p>
        <p>The pattern surfaces in three specific query types:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>"[service] in [city]"</strong> — the classic centroid-triggering query</li>
          <li><strong>"[city] [service]"</strong> — same effect, different word order</li>
          <li><strong>"best [service] [city]"</strong> — geographic prominence still weighs on results</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Why the algorithm behaves this way</div>
          <p>When a searcher types "dentist in Austin" without specifying a neighborhood, Google needs a default reference point for the distance-ranking factor. It uses the <strong>geographic center of the named city</strong> — which mathematically favors businesses located near downtown or the CBD.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why centroid bias matters for local businesses</h2>
        <p>Centroid bias creates lopsided visibility in a way that few other local ranking factors do. Three reasons it deserves close attention:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Structural disadvantage for suburban businesses.</strong> Even with better reviews, more citations, and stronger content, a suburban competitor may lose to a mediocre downtown competitor on citywide queries.</li>
          <li><strong>Location-dependent visibility.</strong> Rankings shift based on where the searcher stands. A geo-grid rank tracker often shows dramatic ranking cliffs 3-5 miles from the business location.</li>
          <li><strong>Multi-location strategy pressure.</strong> Brands considering expansion often use centroid analysis to decide where to open — proximity to city center still commands measurable SEO value.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How centroid bias actually works</h2>
        <p>The algorithm blends three signals for local pack ranking: proximity, prominence, and relevance. Centroid bias sits inside the proximity signal.</p>

        <h3>Reference point problem</h3>
        <p>For queries like "dentist in Austin", Google can't use the searcher's exact location as the reference — the searcher typed a city name. Instead the algorithm assumes the city's centroid. A business 8 miles from centroid is effectively 8 miles away for scoring purposes, even if the searcher is standing next to that business.</p>

        <h3>Post-Vicinity behaviour</h3>
        <p>The November 2021 Vicinity Update tightened proximity's radius. Google shifted toward using the searcher's precise GPS location where available (especially on mobile). Centroid bias didn't disappear — it retreated to desktop searches and to queries where Google can't get a good GPS fix.</p>

        <h3>Prominence as the counter</h3>
        <p>Prominence signals (review count, citation quality, local backlinks, mention frequency) can partially override proximity. A suburban business with 3-4x the reviews of downtown competitors can leapfrog into local pack results despite the distance handicap.</p>

        <h2 id="types">How different query types respond to centroid bias</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Query type</th><th>Reference point</th><th>Centroid bias impact</th><th>Best counter</th></tr>
            </thead>
